rural people. As elsewhere in the Communist Bloc, the Albanian regime borrowed developmental projects from the past and implemented them using social mobilization and a command economy. The abundant archival resources along with interviews in the field attest to the authorities’ efforts to increase consumption and to radically transform people’s tastes. But the book argues that despite the repressive environment, people involved in the sugar project were not simply passive receivers of models from the nation's capital. The author also describes that—in defiance of Cold War bipolarity—technological requirements and social policy considerations required a degree of engagement with the broader world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCommunismzAlbania. 0aRural development projectszAlbaniazMaliq (Korçë)xHistoryy20th century. 0aSugar beet industryzAlbaniazMaliq (Korçë)xHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  acountryside.  aglobalization.  aindustrialization.  amodernization.  asocialism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2023z978311079759640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789633866177?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633866177423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633866177/original  a978-3-11-079759-6  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK